export const VOLUMES = {"I":{"title":"Above the treeline, each in its working season","intro":"High mountains share a grammar — bleached rock, wind-pruned scrub, glacial water that is never the blue of a swimming pool — but the species and stone change with the hemisphere. These four are sampled at the elevation where forest gives out. Each refuses the travel-poster snowcap: the colour that actually fills the eye at altitude is rock, lichen, and dead grass, not white."},"II":{"title":"The northern forest, where conifer meets cold","intro":"The boreal belt circles the globe in a band of spruce, larch, birch, and bog. Its colour is darker and cooler than the deciduous forest to the south, and in winter it reduces almost to graphite and snow. Each refuses the Christmas-card evergreen: real taiga green is blue-black and sparse, set against muskeg rust and lichen grey."},"III":{"title":"The wet forest, where everything is green on green","intro":"Temperate rainforest is the densest green on earth — moss on bark on fern on nurse log — but read closely it is a dozen greens plus the brown of decay and the tannin-black of its streams. The challenge is to find the structure inside the green. Each refuses the flat 'jungle green': the real forest separates into moss, conifer, fern, and rot, each a distinct hue."},"IV":{"title":"Beyond the trees, where ground-cover replaces forest","intro":"Above and beyond the treeline the world flattens to lichen, dwarf shrub, rock, and ice. The colour is low and wide — but in autumn the tundra briefly burns red and gold across whole hillsides. Each refuses the all-white polar cliché: the Arctic is rust, ochre, and ground-hugging crimson far more of the year than it is snow."},"V":{"title":"The dry lands, where the rock outshouts the plants","intro":"Deserts are mineral landscapes: the dominant colour is almost always the ground itself — iron-red sand, salt-white pan, copper rock — with sparse vegetation reduced to silver and grey. Light is hard and shadows are sharp. Each refuses the empty-golden-dune cliché: real deserts are specific reds, whites, and ochres set by the local mineralogy, with one or two living greens."},"VI":{"title":"The hot forest, where the brights live in flashes","intro":"Tropical rainforest reads as a wall of green, but its identity is set by the flashes that punctuate it — a macaw, a poison frog, a heliconia — against muddy water and leaf-litter brown. The structure is dark green base, loud rare accent. Each refuses the candy-bright jungle: the forest is mostly shadow and mud, and the colour earns its loudness by being rare."},"VII":{"title":"Where land and water blur, reed by reed","intro":"Wetlands are horizontal worlds of reed, water, and sky, their colour set by the plant that dominates the marsh and the way light lies flat across open water. They shift hard between seasons — green flood to gold dry. Each refuses the murky-swamp cliché: wetlands are luminous, with sky-water and reed-gold doing most of the work."},"VIII":{"title":"The open ground, all grass and sky and dust","intro":"Grasslands are dominated by two huge fields — the grass and the sky — with everything else a small punctuation: a tree, an animal, a flower. The grass colour is set by the season: green flush, gold cure, grey dormancy. Each refuses the lush-green-meadow default: most of the year, grassland is cured gold and dust, not spring green."},"IX":{"title":"The tide line, where water meets the living rock","intro":"The coast is an edge biome, its colour split between the water's blue-green and the dark, encrusted intertidal zone. Each shore is set by its dominant organism — coral, rockweed, mangrove, kelp — and the temperature of its sea. Each refuses the brochure-beach turquoise: most productive coasts are cold, dark, and weed-covered, with brightness coming from the life, not the water."},"X":{"title":"The restless ground, where chemistry colours the earth","intro":"Volcanic country is coloured by mineralogy and microbiology: sulphur yellow, iron red, obsidian black, and the impossible blues and oranges of thermophile-rich pools. The base is dark rock; the accents are chemical and intense. Each refuses the generic lava-orange: real geothermal colour is the mineral stain and the microbial mat, far stranger than a glow."},"XI":{"title":"Below the surface, lit by a single shaft","intro":"Underground, colour comes from mineral deposition and the quality of the one light source — a shaft, a lamp, a glow. The base is near-black; everything is read against the dark, which makes even pale stone glow. Each refuses the flat-black 'cave' cliché: subterranean palettes are about luminous mineral against shadow, not an absence of colour."},"XII":{"title":"The broadleaf wood, tuned to a single season","intro":"Deciduous woodland is the great colour-changer: the same forest is bluebell-blue in spring, deep green in summer, and a riot of red and gold in autumn. Each palette fixes one moment in that cycle. Each refuses the generic autumn-leaf medley: a real wood at a real moment is dominated by one or two species' colour, not an even confetti of all of them."}};
